Today is the anniversary of the birth of Srinivasa Ramanujan
\f1\b0  
\fs23\fsmilli11900 \cf4 (
\fs28 \cf2 1887-1920), was an Indian {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematician"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 mathematician}} who lived during the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Raj"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 British Rule in India.}} Though he had almost no formal training in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pure_mathematics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 pure mathematics}}, he made substantial contributions to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_analysis"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 mathematical analysis}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 number theory}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_series"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 infinite series}}, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continued_fraction"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 continued fractions}}, including solutions to mathematical problems then considered unsolvable. Ramanujan initially developed his own mathematical research in isolation. Seeking mathematicians who could better understand his work, in 1913 he began a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Postal_service"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 postal}} partnership with the English mathematician {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G._H._Hardy"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 G. H. Hardy}}. Recognizing Ramanujan's work as extraordinary, Hardy arranged for him to travel to Cambridge. \cb1 \
\cb3 During his short life, Ramanujan independently compiled nearly 3,900 results (mostly {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Identity_(mathematics)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 identities}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equation"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 equations}}). Many were completely novel; his original and highly unconventional results, such as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramanujan_prime"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Ramanujan prime}}, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramanujan_theta_function"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Ramanujan theta function}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partition_(number_theory)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 partition}} formulae and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mock_theta_function"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 mock theta functions}}, have opened entire new areas of work and inspired a vast amount of further research. Nearly all his claims have now been proven correct.\cb1 \
\cb3 In 1919, ill health compelled Ramanujan's return to India, where he died in 1920 at the age of 32. \cb1 \
\cb3 A deeply religious {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Hindu}}, Ramanujan credited his substantial mathematical capacities to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divinity"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 divinity}}, and said the mathematical knowledge he displayed was revealed to him by his family goddess. "An equation for me has no meaning," he once said, "unless it expresses a thought of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/God_in_Hinduism"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 God}}."
